🚨Long Post Alert 🚨 

It takes giant Disco Balls 🪩 to sing Whitney. No one should (except Amber Iman who was doing this cover before it was cool… 🙏🏼) 

BUT

I can’t do my Rewind show without talking about the voice that just was my musical obsession. Half of this video is in NY with my band led by the brilliant Yas Fukuoka. The second half is the genius Matt Gould (who Gould-Ified) the ending as only he can live in LA. 

BACKSTORY:

The year was 1990, I was seven years old and my parents put on the new Whitney “I’m Your Baby Tonight” album…. I was hooked. 

I had never heard someone sound more beautiful, be more beautiful, and connect to a song like she did. I was obsessed. She made me want to sing. She was joy. She was JERSEY! 

That obsession only grew thru the years. The good & bad times never stopped me from knowing she was THE VOICE. The voice of a generation. The cadence, tone, control, no one tops it. 

I remember seeing her at MSG and sitting a row away from Luther and Brandy, I remember meeting her in NY and her saying to me “I have to sing baby…,” I remember going to GMA when “Just Whitney” & “I Look To You” came out. I remember so many sing alongs and movie nights to her work. Speed up to today and getting to talk to MD to the stars Ricky Minor about his life and times with her- SURREAL! 

It’s sad that sometimes someone has to be gone to get their due. I am happy with the movie, the music, and the new appreciation that has been found for her. I wish we could have given it to her while she was alive. 

Let’s remember some kindness and compassion. You never know what someone is going thru. “A few stolen moments is all that we share….” 💜

When people ask me to sing the national anthem, a song I’ve been singing since I am 11 years old, (find the footage of me at MSG for a good laugh) it’s supposed to be an honor. It is an honor. I sing it when asked with the prayer that one day “liberty and justice for all” will truly ring true for ALL.

Honored to be represent Jersey & Pride. Pride is a protest even in December. 
🌈✊🏻

Years ago, when I did “Rent,” a friend of mine said on the last show, “Now things can go back to normal,” and I said “I don’t think it will be “normal” ever again…” and it sure hasn’t been. 

This year was filled with love, art, loss, heartbreak, and a lot of joy. It might have been the best one yet. I have never felt more free, authentic, and alive. Professionally, yeah all has grown and is growing with so many goals and dreams ahead, but more important, personally, I feel the same way. Let’s keep going and growing. 

Thank you to my family and friends who hold me all the way down, all the amazing people who I have talked to, sung with, and worked with this year. My babies in the classroom and not for the joy, and for all of you who root, cheer, and support me- I love and appreciate you! Let’s March into 2023 with the audacity to know that the best is still to come! Happy New Year! 🎆

We came. We sang. We conquered. 

Thanks for all the love and support! Thanks to the NJ Devils and all the Pride organizations that made the night possible. It was such a fun way to close out performing in 2022! More to come in 2023! ❤️

Here is a little story for you:

In 2021, I released an album entitled “Unfinished Business” that was made during the pandemic. It featured all live musicians, duets, and was self funded by little ole me! We were so excited to put the album out and be streamed thousands of times, sold thousands of CD’s on Amazon and be seen on YouTube over 250k times! 

When the smoke cleared, I received a check for $330 dollars after paying for it all myself. Why? That’s the record game. That’s the life of an artist. 

So I decided when my two year contract was up, I wanted to own my album and be in control. So guess what’s back? Unfinished Business is back out and up on all steaming platforms! 

If you have listened in the past, or have never heard a moment- now is the time to check us out! Every little stream counts! 

Thanks to Robbie Rozelle for helping with this! Thanks to all the artists who are on this project with me, and mostly thanks to each of you for streaming and sharing and singing along!

This week we are talking BABS! Attention- Fire Island! 

Jonathan Tolins’ Buyer and Cellar will make its Fire Island debut via The Arts Project of Cherry Grove with two performances August 4 and 5, both at 8 PM. Jack Bartholet is starring with Travis Greisler directing.

Inspired by Barbra Streisand’s very real basement of storefronts in her Malibu home used to store her collection of dolls and other tchotchkes, Tolins’ solo play imagines a very not real gay man who’s hired to be the sole employee of the fake stores. Michael Urie won a Drama Desk Award starring in the play’s 2013 Off-Broadway premiere, a production that would ultimately transfer to a commercial Off-Broadway run of a year.

“Alex, the main character I play, is entranced by a larger-than-life pop star diva,” says Bartholet. “This is a familiar dynamic for gay men, so Fire Island seems a particularly rich place for relatability. He’s also an actor with a boyfriend who has gay showbiz-encyclopedia knowledge and passion—the gays will get nearly every joke. I really enjoy the imaginative work of Jonathan Tolins. I’d love to live inside his brain for a day. In this fantasy, Barbra Streisand encourages Alex to demand respect. She elevates his taste and teaches him a few lessons…it’s a lovely journey. The play is hysterical, and I can’t wait to dive into this world when the curtain rises.”

Tickets are available at RedEyeTickets.com. Full chat available on YouTube! Link in bio!

To a young Tom Sweitzer in 1970s blue-collar Pennsylvania, homemade meatballs were an Italian mom’s cure-all. Husky pants from Sears were a necessary evil. And dad’s schizophrenia and alcoholism were the fuel to a nightmarish fire. That is the life Tom knew and endured until one day, he ran out of the house and into the church across the street. There, he met a woman who gave him a gift that would alter the course of his life: music. Through song, Tom found a haven, a passion, a career, and a purpose. But above all, it gave him the language to accept loss, let in love, and forgive the demons of his past.

20 Seconds is an inspiring testimony to the uplifting power of music at all stages of life. Music provided companionship when Tom couldn’t find it in a destructive home. Years later, music shaped Tom’s career as a therapist, allowing him to augment his penchant for song with clinical, research-based practices.

In his inviting solo performance, Tom weaves storytelling with original song and nearly a dozen colorful characters. Over 90 minutes, audiences meet the Sunday school savior, the compassionate but ailing mother, the tortured father, one foul-mouthed parrot, and many more. As you follow him through his journey, you’ll hear the music that shaped his healing, and, as the church bells chime across the street, experience the powerful 20 seconds that mended a scarred relationship between a father and son.

“Tom Sweitzer is a composer and artist with vision, and he delivers an emotional and compelling autobiographical performance. He survived extraordinary challenges in his childhood and discovered a talent for music that, as a Music Therapist, enables him generously to give others what he never received. This is a portrait of resilience and forgiveness.” - Renée Fleming

There has never been a time for a piece like this! We in the US often see things thru the lens of our culture, laws, and government. Have you thought about Trans Lives & Religion in other lands?

Award-winning director Ahmad Alyaseer’s latest film, OUR MALES AND FEMALES, is a story of the harrowing injustice faced by a deceased transgender woman in the Middle East as her family grapples with the task of washing the body and coming to terms with their “son’s” new identity. The short, a powerful exploration of the complexities of gender identity, grief and religion, has not only captivated audiences worldwide but has also just secured its place as a strong contender for the 2024 Academy Awards®.

The film has so far garnered widespread attention and acclaim during its impressive festival run, participating in more than 90 film festivals across the globe and being screened in over 35 countries. Nonetheless, the film still faces challenges in its home region, the Middle East, where censorship issues have prevented its screening, underscoring the critical nature of the themes explored in OUR MALES AND FEMALES.
Ahmad Alyaseer, an award-winning writer and director from Jordan, masterfully weaved this gripping narrative that continues to spark conversations about gender identity and acceptance.
